	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Clock Speeds</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />From what I've read, the PAL NES runs on a different clock speed than the NTSC counterpart and ends up executing instructions a little bit slower. I have two questions:
<br />
<br />1) What is the external clock speed into the 2A07?
<br />2) If #1 is less than 21.47727 MHz, why is there a whole different processor? 
<br />
<br />I'm really curious how flexible the clocking on a 2A03 is. I don't imagine it can go down to DC, but it seems like it should run at speeds other than 21.47727 MHz.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Wed Mar 11, 2009 12:41 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Clock Speeds</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">skrasms wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">1) What is the external clock speed into the 2A07?</div><br />The NES master clock frequency is always six times the color subcarrier frequency. For PAL, this is defined as 4,433,618.75 Hz.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">2) If #1 is less than 21.47727 MHz, why is there a whole different processor?</div>
<br />The 2A03 divides by 12. The 2A07 divides by 16 because Nintendo was too cheap to divide by 15, which would have preserved the ratio of three pixels per CPU cycle.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


